  1. West Wing Tours are selective, how many are being taken?

WHERE WE ARE AT RIGHT NOW: Shaun are you working on this one? There’s nothing in the group notebook for this but we do have the analysis done looking at the data for the cocaine day. Might be good to look at the # of ppl who did west wing tours that day specifically and the mean / median # of ppl who visit for west wing tours normally.

On July 2, cocaine was found at the White House. 1994 people visited the White House that day, presumably most of them tourists. (Hard to imagine where all those people could have fit though.) Finding out whether this was an unusal amount of people proved to be quite a challenge thanks to what we realized was a strange quirk in the data. On some days, tens of thousands of visitors went to the White House, on others, only a few hundred. The mean number of visitors was 33,801 but that’s thrown off by a couple days with an insanely high number of visitors. The median is a more reasonable, 139. The mean being so different than the median led us to wonder if Biden had suddenly started received way more visitors as time has went on? We made a scatterplot to see, and our answer was: No, not really. There did not seem to be any rhyme or reason to when more people came, the days with thousands of people were pretty random. So we dug into the dates with thousands of people allegedly visiting the White House some more. We identified something pretty strange: The people racking up thousands upon thousands of visits were not the president, were not the vice president, were not important people in the cabinet. It was a pretty random assortment of comparatively unimportant people got the same number of visitors over and over again. On 12/01/2022, the day French President Emmanuel Macron visited the White House, for example, several groups of 5,619 people allegedly toured the White House to visit Kevin Ballen, a literally-just-graduated Harvard alum who completed a bachelor’s. Not Joe Biden. Similar trends could be observed with other days, with the same large number of people visiting seemingly unimportant people.

Let’s clean our data a little bit better.

#used chatgpt to do this it took forever. It kept giving me code to change the last name from potus to Biden but tolower(visitee_namelast_clean) %in% c("potus") ~ "Joe" would not work. I asked it: can you help me write a case when for the following conditions: if visitee_namelast_clean == Potus or potus or POTUS,  change visitee_namelast_clean to Biden and visitee_namefirst_clean to Joe. 

#It gave me the following code but with tolower(visitee_namelast_clean) %in% c("potus") ~ "Joe" - i finally figured out it was because I had already changed the visitee_namelast_clean column in the code above so it wouldn't recognize "potus" in the visitee_namelast_clean col to change the first name to Joe. 

wh_visitor_data <- wh_visitor_data |>
  mutate(
    visitee_namelast_clean = case_when(
      tolower(visitee_namelast_clean) %in% c("potus") ~ "Biden",
      tolower(visitee_namelast_clean) %in% c("vpotus") ~ "Harris",
      tolower(visitee_namelast_clean) %in% c("flotus") ~ "Biden",
      TRUE ~ visitee_namelast_clean
    ),
    visitee_namefirst_clean = case_when(
      tolower(visitee_namelast) %in% c("potus") ~ "Joe",
      tolower(visitee_namelast) %in% c("vpotus") ~ "Kamala",
      tolower(visitee_namelast) %in% c("flotus") ~ "Jill",
      TRUE ~ visitee_namefirst_clean
    )
  )
